canonical:
  title: 上疏不報辭職表
  author: 金富軾
  language: lzh
  text: 明聖作爲謂無闕政愚臣冒犯合置常刑中謝 臣有泥古之愚無周身之智當官論事實昧變通伏閤上書不知忘諱公乏分毫之益私蒙媿恥之深事至如斯身何足惜伏望擧國正典罪臣狂言更選忠良以備諫職望闕拜表涕洟交切謹先着白衫詣東上閤門祗候某臣甞受職牒告身幾道同在進納
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 上疏不報辭職表
  author: 金富軾
  language: lzh
  text: 明聖作爲。謂無闕政。愚臣冒犯。合置常刑。中謝。 臣有泥古之愚。無周身之智。當官論事。實昧變通。伏閤上書。不知忘諱。公乏分毫之益。私蒙媿恥之深。事至如斯。身何足惜。伏望擧國正典。罪臣狂言。更選忠良。以備諫職。望闕拜表。涕洟交切。謹先着白衫詣東上閤門祗候某。臣甞受職牒告身幾道。同在進納。
korean:
  title: 상소 불보사직 표
  author: 김부식
  language: kor
  text: 명성(明聖)의 하시는 일은 실책이 없다 이르옵는데, 우신(愚臣)이 함부로 위엄을 범하였사오니, 정한 형에 처함이 합당하옵니다. 중사(中謝) 신은 옛것만 고집하는 어리석음이 있사옵고 몸을 두루 살필 지혜가 없사오므로 관에 있어 일을 논하면 실로 변통에 어둡사옵고, 대궐문에 엎드려 글월을 올리오면 기휘(忌諱)할 줄 모르오며, 공적으로는 털끝만큼도 유익됨이 없사옵고 사적으로는 낯이 부끄러운 은혜를 입었사오니, 일이 이 지경에 이르므로 몸이 무엇이 아깝겠사옵니까. 엎드려 바라옵건대, 국가의 정법[正典]에 비추어 신의 광언(狂言)을 죄주시고, 다시 충량(忠良)을 선택하시와 간직(諫職)에 비치하시옵소서. 대궐을 바라보고 표에 절하오니 눈물 콧물이 함께 흐르옵니다. 삼가 먼저 흰 옷을 입고 동으로 나아가 합문지후(閤門祗候) 아무개에게 올리오며, 신이 일찍이 받자온 직첩과 고신(告身) 몇 통도 동봉하여 올리옵니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0450_010_0040&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial on Resignation Following Failure of Remonstrance
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty's wise governance is said to be without flaw, yet this foolish minister has rashly transgressed your dignity and deserves the prescribed punishment.

    I confess: I am bound by the stubbornness of antiquity and lack the wisdom to navigate all circumstances. In office, when I speak of affairs, I am truly blind to adaptation. When I bow and present my words at the palace gate, I know not how to guard against offense. In service to the state, I have brought not even the smallest benefit, while privately bearing the deep shame of your grace. When matters have come to this pass, what is my life worth preserving?

    I humbly beseech that by the nation's righteous law you judge this minister's reckless words as crime, and instead select worthy and virtuous men to fill the role of remonstrance. Bowing toward the distant palace, my tears and tears intermingle as I submit this memorial. I respectfully don white robes and present this first to the Gate Attendant of the Eastern Gate, and I enclose herewith the several diplomas and official certificates that I once received.
  footnotes:
    - This memorial represents the formal ritual of remonstration and resignation in Korean court politics, where a minister who failed to effect change through his counsel sought to resign in shame while accepting punishment for his presumption.
